Yes, governance tooling can help collect metrics and export useful data partially, but not fully.

Why is it partially 


It is partially because governance tooling gives you some important operational data, but not complete appliance observability.

What It Can Give You

Governance / CLI / Governor tools are strong for:

Audit logs (who did what)
Repo inventory
Workflow / Actions usage
Git traffic patterns
Clone / fetch / push behavior
Hot repositories
Concurrency / load from Git operations
Structured exports (JSON / reports)

That means it helps explain usage behavior and GitHub activity.

What It Cannot Fully Give You

It usually does not provide full deep infrastructure monitoring such as:

Real-time CPU saturation
Full memory pressure / leaks
Disk I/O bottlenecks
Network latency
OS-level host health
Detailed service crashes
End-to-end request latency across all services
Advanced alerting / anomaly detection

That requires tools like Datadog or Splunk.

Easy Analogy

Governance tooling is like checking the airport passenger list and flight schedule.
You can see who traveled and where traffic is heavy.

But it doesn’t tell you whether the engine is overheating or the runway lights failed.

Best Demo Line

“Governance tooling provides strong visibility into user activity, Git load, and operational patterns, but it does not replace dedicated infrastructure monitoring. That’s why it is a partial solution rather than a complete observability solution.”
